snippet.textDisplay:
AB - Thanks for posting these. And thank you for all the Good Eats, classic and reloaded. To this day, whenever I search for a recipe I haven't made before, I always first search for the "dish name" + "alton brown", because that's the best way to get a complete view of of the dish, instead of just a list of things to mix.
I don't know if you look at these comments, but if you do, I have a sincere challenge for you or anyone else reading this.
I used to absolutely love saltines. I don't know what it is about them, but they were always such a rich and satisfying flavor and experience. To this day I still often have cravings specifically for saltines.
Ok, all the past tense... I have Celiac disease. I haven't (intentionally) had a saltine or any gluten containing food since 2001. No sympathy needed. There are soooo very many worse things to have to deal with. BUT, I have not been able to come up with either any commercial products or recipes for gluten-free saltine crackers that are any good. I bake and I'll have a go at any reasonable recipes. Rice flour? Meh. Rice crackers are absolutely nothing like saltines. Every recipe I've tried has been disappointing at best.
So, now with some time available, are you up for taking a run at a Good Eats gluten-free saltine?

snippet.textDisplay: People skip on saltines (Soda crackers where I'm from) but they're just a snack waiting to happen. You can basically put anything on them. Saltines with peanut butter is a very basic but delicious snack, but I also recall recipes like saltine toffee, in which you line the tray with crackers, then pour over a boiled mixture of melted butter and brown sugar, optionally add nuts or whatever I guess. Bake. My favorite recipe from our family christmas platters it simply crushed ritz crackers mixed with sweetened condensed milk and some skor/butterscotch chips, pressed into a pan and topped with icing though it can do without. It's time to be adventurous with our shelf stable ingredients!
